  {
    "id": "UgzL8P5j8PGUxdsJ1F14AaABAg",
    "author": "@glencahalin4786",
    "author_channel_id": "UCfIFc1xQ_3rGeQ83D2FyU3A",
    "text": "I'm wondering about if having a rotation component, to the print head holder, could cause it's own problem. An example might be printing a thin cylinder, in software the most efficient pathway would be to set the radius and keep rotating. However I suspect that would lead to twists in the filament and wires going to the printhead. A software solution might be to possible to never cross ( say )  the zero degree mark but to always reverse direction at that point. Not sure if that would end up leaving a slight seem in practice.\n\nIt occurred to me then that, maybe if was the base plate that was designed as the rotational component, it would eliminate that ( possible ) problem.\n Of course it might introduce one of it's own eg if the mass and momentum of moving a bigger print and baseplate would start to make things overshoot. At the sizes being looked at probably not but if scaling up I'd expect to have to add something like an adjustable friction brake.",
    "likes": 0,
    "published_at": "2025-07-18T18:51:12Z",
    "reply_count": 0,
    "replies": []
  },
  {
    "id": "UgwA0kt1TnOZoj_ERMN4AaABAg",
    "author": "@kalvenism",
    "author_channel_id": "UCaHzsbJNfXqz9yRqvQQ0Nmw",
    "text": "Just out of curiosity on a slightly different subject(z-axis motor coupler), do you believe a coupler that the lead screw actually screws into (rather than being clamped in as with current coupler design) would be helpful in eliminating z-binding?",
    "likes": 0,
    "published_at": "2025-07-18T13:46:17Z",
    "reply_count": 0,
    "replies": []
  },
